    "id": "pass_172",
    "title": "Negligence and the Duty of Care",
    "text": "Negligence is a branch of civil law that allows a person who has suffered harm to claim compensation from someone whose carelessness caused that harm. A claim in negligence does not depend on any deliberate intention to injure. Instead, it rests on the idea that people owe one another a duty to take reasonable care when their actions might foreseeably affect others. Drivers owe a duty to other road users, employers owe a duty to their staff, and manufacturers owe a duty to the people who use their products. Where such a duty exists and is broken, the law may require the careless party to pay damages.\n\nTo succeed, a claimant must usually establish three things. First, the defendant owed the claimant a duty of care. Second, the defendant breached that duty by falling below the standard expected of a reasonable person in the circumstances. Third, the breach actually caused the loss or injury complained of, and that loss was not too remote a consequence of the carelessness. If any of these elements is missing, the claim will normally fail. A defendant who took every reasonable precaution is rarely held liable, even when harm still occurs, because the law does not demand perfection.\n\nThe standard of care expected can vary with the situation. A professional such as a surgeon or an accountant is generally judged against the standard of a competent member of that profession, not that of an ordinary person. Children are often held to a lower standard than adults. Some jurists argue that these varying standards make negligence unpredictable, while others maintain that flexibility allows the law to respond fairly to very different circumstances.",
