    "id": "pass_177",
    "title": "Defamation",
    "text": "Defamation is the area of civil law concerned with protecting a person's reputation against false statements. A statement is generally defamatory if it would tend to lower the person in the eyes of ordinary, reasonable members of society, for example by suggesting dishonesty, incompetence, or serious misconduct. Defamation is often divided into two kinds. Libel usually refers to statements made in a lasting form, such as writing, print, or broadcast, while slander usually refers to spoken words and other more temporary forms.\n\nTo bring a successful claim, the person suing must normally show that the statement referred to them, that it was communicated to at least one other person, and that it carried a defamatory meaning. In many systems the claimant does not have to prove that the statement was false, because the law presumes falsity and leaves it to the defendant to prove the truth if they can. Some jurisdictions also require the claimant to show that the statement caused, or was likely to cause, serious harm to their reputation before a claim can proceed.\n\nSeveral defences are available to a person accused of defamation. The most obvious is truth: a statement that is substantially true is generally not actionable, however damaging it may be. Another common defence is honest opinion, which may protect comment that is clearly presented as a personal view rather than a statement of fact. There is also often a defence of privilege, which protects statements made on certain public occasions, such as debates in a legislature or evidence given in court. Some argue that defamation law can silence legitimate criticism, while others maintain that it provides necessary protection against damaging falsehoods.",
