    "id": "pass_178",
    "title": "Self-Defence in Criminal Law",
    "text": "Self-defence is a principle that allows a person to use force in certain situations without committing a crime. Ordinarily, deliberately striking or injuring another person would amount to an offence. However, the law recognises that people are sometimes entitled to protect themselves, others, or their property from attack, and that force used for such a purpose may be lawful. Where the defence applies successfully, a person who would otherwise be guilty of an offence such as assault may be acquitted.\n\nThe defence is usually subject to two main conditions. First, the use of force must have been necessary in the circumstances as the person honestly believed them to be. A person who genuinely, even if mistakenly, believes they are under attack may still rely on the defence, provided the belief was honestly held. Second, the amount of force used must be reasonable and proportionate to the threat faced. Force that goes well beyond what the situation required is unlikely to be excused, and a person who continues to attack an assailant who no longer poses any danger may lose the protection of the defence.\n\nThe law does not generally expect a person facing sudden danger to weigh the exact degree of force to a nicety. Someone acting in the heat of the moment may use force that later appears slightly excessive and still be treated as having acted reasonably. There is often no strict duty to retreat before defending oneself, though the possibility of retreat may be one factor in deciding whether the response was reasonable. Some argue that the rules give too much latitude to those who use violence, while others maintain that people must be free to protect themselves effectively.",
