    "id": "pass_179",
    "title": "Intellectual Property",
    "text": "Intellectual property refers to legal rights that protect creations of the mind, such as inventions, written works, designs, and brand names. Unlike ownership of physical objects, these rights concern intangible things: ideas expressed in a particular form, or signs that identify a business. The law grants creators and businesses a period of control over their work so that they can benefit from it, on the theory that this encourages innovation and creativity.\n\nSeveral distinct kinds of intellectual property are commonly recognised. Copyright protects original literary, artistic, and musical works, and it usually arises automatically as soon as the work is created, without any need for registration. It does not protect ideas themselves, only the particular expression of them. A patent protects a new invention, giving the inventor exclusive rights to use it for a limited number of years, but a patent must generally be applied for and granted, and the invention must be genuinely new and useful. A trade mark protects a sign, such as a name or logo, that distinguishes the goods or services of one business from those of another. Registered designs protect the appearance of a product.\n\nMost intellectual property rights last only for a limited time. Patents, for instance, typically expire after a set number of years, after which the invention may be used freely by anyone. Copyright usually lasts much longer, often for many decades after the creator's death, before the work enters the public domain. Some commentators argue that strong intellectual property rights reward creators fairly and fund further research. Others maintain that overly long or broad protection can restrict access to knowledge and slow the spread of useful ideas.",
