    "id": "pass_185",
    "title": "Statutory Interpretation",
    "text": "Statutory interpretation is the process by which courts work out the meaning of laws passed by a legislature. Although statutes are drafted with care, the words used cannot foresee every situation, and disputes often arise about how a provision should apply to particular facts. When this happens, it falls to the courts to decide what the words were intended to mean and how they should be applied. The way judges approach this task can significantly affect the outcome of a case.\n\nSeveral approaches have traditionally been used. One approach gives the words of the statute their ordinary, literal meaning, on the basis that this is what the legislature actually enacted and that judges should not rewrite the law. A difficulty with this approach is that a strictly literal reading can sometimes produce an absurd or unjust result that the legislature plainly did not intend. A second approach therefore allows the court to depart from the literal meaning where it would lead to absurdity, choosing instead a sensible interpretation. A third approach looks more broadly at the purpose behind the statute, asking what problem the law was meant to address and reading the words in a way that advances that aim.\n\nCourts may also rely on various aids to interpretation. They may consider the statute as a whole, so that individual words are read in their context, and they may apply long established presumptions, such as the presumption that a statute does not take away existing rights unless it says so clearly. Some jurists argue that judges should stay close to the literal text to respect the authority of the legislature. Others maintain that seeking the purpose of a law produces fairer and more workable results.",
